proposals.codeSnippet:
// Track multiple touch points in your Touch handler
private readonly Dictionary<long, SKPoint> touchPoints = new();

void OnTouch(object sender, SKTouchEventArgs e)
{
    switch (e.ActionType)
    {
        case SKTouchAction.Pressed:
            touchPoints[e.Id] = e.Location;
            break;
        case SKTouchAction.Moved:
            touchPoints[e.Id] = e.Location;
            if (touchPoints.Count == 2)
            {
                // Calculate pinch/pan from the two points
                var points = touchPoints.Values.ToArray();
                var distance = SKPoint.Distance(points[0], points[1]);
                var center = new SKPoint(
                    (points[0].X + points[1].X) / 2,
                    (points[0].Y + points[1].Y) / 2);
                // Use distance for zoom, center for pan
            }
            break;
        case SKTouchAction.Released:
        case SKTouchAction.Cancelled:
            touchPoints.Remove(e.Id);
            break;
    }
    e.Handled = true;
}

payload.draftBody:
Thanks for the report and the repro project.

The root cause is an architectural difference between iOS and Android touch handling in SkiaSharp. On iOS, SkiaSharp uses a `UIGestureRecognizer` that naturally coexists with other gesture recognizers. On Android, it subscribes to the `View.Touch` event and marks events as handled, which prevents framework gesture recognizers (pinch, pan) from receiving them.

Here's a workaround — handle pinch/pan directly through SkiaSharp's multi-touch events instead of using framework gesture recognizers:

```csharp
private readonly Dictionary<long, SKPoint> touchPoints = new();

void OnTouch(object sender, SKTouchEventArgs e)
{
    switch (e.ActionType)
    {
        case SKTouchAction.Pressed:
            touchPoints[e.Id] = e.Location;
            break;
        case SKTouchAction.Moved:
            touchPoints[e.Id] = e.Location;
            if (touchPoints.Count == 2)
            {
                var points = touchPoints.Values.ToArray();
                var distance = SKPoint.Distance(points[0], points[1]);
                var center = new SKPoint(
                    (points[0].X + points[1].X) / 2,
                    (points[0].Y + points[1].Y) / 2);
                // Use distance for zoom, center for pan
            }
            break;
        case SKTouchAction.Released:
        case SKTouchAction.Cancelled:
            touchPoints.Remove(e.Id);
            break;
    }
    e.Handled = true;
}
```

Note: Xamarin.Forms is now deprecated. If you experience the same issue in .NET MAUI, please open a new issue so we can track it specifically.
